+# Task 012.3 --- Android Data Layer, Repositories, and Synchronization
+
+Status: DONE
+
+## Objective
+
+Create the repository's third production educational topic package.
+
+The topic must teach how the Android Data layer provides application
+data through repositories, coordinates local and remote data sources,
+defines a Single Source of Truth (SSOT), handles caching and
+synchronization, and isolates the rest of the application from storage
+and transport details.
+
+The topic builds on:
+
+-   Task 012.1 --- Android App Architecture Foundations
+-   Task 012.2 --- Android UI Layer and Unidirectional Data Flow
+
+------------------------------------------------------------------------
+
+## Scope
+
+Create exactly one production topic package:
+
+`content/android/app-architecture/android-data-layer-repositories-and-synchronization/`
+
+The package must contain exactly:
+
+-   topic.yaml
+-   theory.md
+-   cheat-sheet.md
+-   practice.md
+-   interview.md
+-   test.yaml
+
+------------------------------------------------------------------------
+
+## Topic metadata
+
+-   **id:** android-data-layer-repositories-and-synchronization
+-   **track:** android
+-   **section:** app-architecture
+-   **difficulty:** foundation
+-   **status:** review
+-   **content_version:** 1
+-   **estimated_minutes:** 150
+
+### Prerequisites
+
+-   android-app-architecture-foundations
+-   android-ui-layer-and-unidirectional-data-flow
+
+------------------------------------------------------------------------
+
+## Educational goal
+
+Teach the learner to reason about:
+
+-   Data layer responsibilities
+-   Repository responsibilities
+-   Data sources
+-   Local vs remote sources
+-   Single Source of Truth
+-   Read and write paths
+-   Caching
+-   Synchronization
+-   Offline-capable architectures
+-   Data freshness
+-   Conflict handling
+-   Mapping between transport, persistence, domain and UI models
+
+The topic must focus on architectural responsibilities rather than
+Retrofit, Room, SQL or HTTP APIs.
+
+------------------------------------------------------------------------
+
+## Required conceptual model
+
+``` text
+UI / Domain
+     ↓
+ Repository
+     ↓
+Data source coordination
+ ↙               ↘
+Local          Remote
+     ↓
+Application data
+```
+
+Also explain local-first synchronization:
+
+``` text
+Remote
+   ↓
+Persist locally
+   ↓
+Observe local storage
+   ↓
+Expose updated application data
+```
+
+Clarify that these are conceptual responsibility flows, not mandatory
+class diagrams.
+
+------------------------------------------------------------------------
+
+## Learning outcomes
+
+The learner should be able to:
+
+-   explain Data layer responsibilities;
+-   distinguish repositories from data sources;
+-   identify the SSOT;
+-   analyze read and write paths;
+-   compare cache-first, network-first and local-first strategies;
+-   explain synchronization trade-offs;
+-   identify responsibility leaks;
+-   design a basic offline-capable architecture.
+
+------------------------------------------------------------------------
+
+## Required theory structure
+
+1.  Why the Data layer exists
+2.  Repository responsibilities
+3.  Data sources
+4.  Repository vs Data source
+5.  Data ownership
+6.  Single Source of Truth
+7.  Read paths
+8.  Write paths
+9.  Caching
+10. Data freshness
+11. Refresh strategies
+12. Offline-first architectures
+13. Synchronization
+14. Conflict handling
+15. Error boundaries
+16. Model mapping
+17. Repository granularity
+18. Android examples
+19. Common mistakes
+20. Trade-offs
+21. Summary
+
+------------------------------------------------------------------------
+
+## Required coverage
+
+The topic must explain:
+
+-   Repository responsibilities
+-   Local and remote data sources
+-   SSOT
+-   Cache vs persistence
+-   Network-first
+-   Cache-first
+-   Local-first
+-   Synchronization
+-   Retry
+-   Conflict resolution
+-   Data freshness
+-   DTO ↔ Entity ↔ Domain ↔ UI mapping
+
+Do not prescribe a single architecture as universally correct.
+
+------------------------------------------------------------------------
+
+## Kotlin examples
+
+Include at least:
+
+``` kotlin
+interface UserRepository {
+    fun observeUser(id: String): Flow<User?>
+    suspend fun refreshUser(id: String)
+    suspend fun updateUserName(id: String, name: String)
+}
+```
+
+Include a repository coordinating both local and remote sources.
+
+------------------------------------------------------------------------
+
+## Practice
+
+Create **at least five** exercises:
+
+1.  Responsibility classification
+2.  Repository vs wrapper
+3.  Choosing the SSOT
+4.  Broken synchronization
+5.  Model-boundary analysis
+
+Each exercise must include:
+
+-   task
+-   expected reasoning
+-   reviewer guidance
+
+------------------------------------------------------------------------
+
+## Interview
+
+Include:
+
+-   foundational questions
+-   scenario questions
+-   trade-off questions
+
+Cover:
+
+-   repositories
+-   data sources
+-   SSOT
+-   caching
+-   synchronization
+-   offline-first
+-   mapping
+-   repository granularity
+
+------------------------------------------------------------------------
+
+## Test
+
+Create exactly **12** questions using supported repository question
+types.
+
+Must include:
+
+-   scenario questions
+-   code-analysis questions
+-   SSOT
+-   cache vs persistence
+-   synchronization
+-   repository responsibilities
+
+------------------------------------------------------------------------
+
+## Out of scope
+
+Do not:
+
+-   modify competencies;
+-   modify learning sequences;
+-   teach Retrofit APIs;
+-   teach Room APIs;
+-   teach Flow in depth;
+-   teach dependency injection;
+-   teach MVI libraries.
+
